{"id":"2006.16157","submitter":"C. S. Shahbazi","authors":"C. I. Lazaroiu, C. S. Shahbazi","title":"Four-dimensional geometric supergravity and electromagnetic duality: a\n  brief guide for mathematicians","comments":"Prepared for the proceedings of the Bucharest Conference on Geometry\n  and Physics. 27 pages","journal-ref":"Rev. Roumaine Math. Pures Appl. 66 (2021) 2, 265-306","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DG hep-th math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We give a gentle introduction to the global geometric formulation of the\nbosonic sector of four-dimensional supergravity on an oriented four-manifold\n$M$ of arbitrary topology, providing a geometric characterization of its\nU-duality group. The geometric formulation of four-dimensional supergravity is\nbased on a choice of a vertically Riemannian submersion $\\pi$ over $M$ equipped\nwith a flat Ehresmann connection, which determines the non-linear section sigma\nmodel of the theory, and a choice of flat symplectic vector bundle\n$\\mathcal{S}$ equipped with a positive complex polarization over the total\nspace of $\\pi$, which encodes the inverse gauge couplings and theta angles of\nthe theory and determines its gauge sector. The classical fields of the theory\nconsist of Lorentzian metrics on $M$, global sections of $\\pi$ and two-forms\nvalued in $\\mathcal{S}$ that satisfy an algebraic relation which defines the\nnotion of \\emph{twisted} self-duality in four Lorentzian dimensions. We use\nthis geometric formulation to investigate the group of electromagnetic duality\ntransformations of supergravity, also known as the continuous classical\nU-duality group, which we characterize using a certain short exact sequence of\nautomorphism groups of vector bundles. Moreover, we discuss the general\nstructure of the Killing spinor equations of four-dimensional supergravity,\nproviding several explicit examples and remarking on a few open mathematical\nproblems. This presentation is aimed at mathematicians working in differential\ngeometry.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Jun 2020 16:19:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 31 Aug 2020 23:17:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-02"}
